@node "GENERALINFO" "Description"
Have you missed a decent Bible studying program for Amiga? I have, and although
there has been some viewers already in the Aminet, they seem to be limited to
certain translation versions in the English language. The most widely available
translation used seems to be the VERY old KJV - King James Version. The
programs are also quite old and perhaps not using the most current good
features of the Amiga operating system.

Being a non-English-speaking person I was particularly interested to get my
mother language (Finnish) versions into my Amiga. In Finland the "official"
translation is from the year 1992 and the nearest before that from 1938. Both
of these versions have been made publically available as tar-zip files at
@{"http://ftp.funet.fi" system "OS4:C/URLOpen http://ftp.funet.fi "}, although some restrictions apply. The 1992 files are
copyrighted and for personal use only - read the copyright information file. As
I found these a couple of years ago, I wondered if I could make a simple
reader/finder program to handle these versions. And now it's reality:
BibVision!

@{u}What is BibVision?@{uu}

With BibVision you can:

    * read a single Bible book
    * read multiple books of a Bible simultaneously in separate windows
    * read multiple books of different Bible translations simultaneously
    * do a (pattern matched) search in the book or multiple books
    * copy text to clipboard (standard text.datatype used as a viewer)
    * with a click of a gadget, make all windows show the same chapter & verse
    * browse Bible also through previously set bookmarks or with the
      window history gadgets
    * with v2.0, several enhancements ie. settings handled through application.library
@endnode

@node "REQUIREMENTS" "Requirements"
Required

    * Amiga or equivalent running OS4.1
    * appropriate Bible texts, downloaded from
      for example ftp.funet.fi

Optionally
    * AISS image set of Martin Merz. Download it from
      @{"http://www.masonicons.info" system "OS4:C/URLOpen http://www.masonicons.info"}

@endnode

@node "INSTALLATION" "Installation"
@{u}How to install the program@{uu}

The simplest and the recommended way to install the BibVision is to use the
installation script found in the archive. Simply click the "Install-BibVision"
icon and follow the instructions. If you want to make it the harder way, copy
the whole unarchived directory into suitable directory in your system.
You should also create directory for each Bible translation to be installed.
BibVision supports AmiUpdate updating method.

Minimal working installation consists of:

    * BibVision executable
    * BibVision.database (info about the Bible source file archives)
    * BibVision.guide manual file
    * one or more Bible translations


@{u}How to install the Bibles@{uu}

The main archive doesn't contain the Bible texts. Instead, you should download
the version or the versions you need from some FTP site containing a publically
available translation. The sites containing BibVision-compatible translations
are:

@{"ftp://ftp.funet.fi/pub/doc/religion/christian/Bible/texts/" system "OS4:C/URLOpen http://ftp.funet.fi/pub/doc/religion/christian/Bible/texts/"}

    * King James Version
    * Vulgate
    * Finnish Bible: versions published 1992 and 1938
    * Swedish year 1917 translation
    * Louis Segond (LSG)

@{"http://aminet.net/" system "OS4:C/URLOpen http://aminet.net/"}

    * German Luther Bible translation


@{u}The FUNET archives are:@{uu}

King James Version
    * .../texts/english/av.tar.gz

Vulgate
    * .../texts/latin/vulgate.tar.gz

Finnish 1992 version
    * .../texts/finnish/1992/VT.tar.gz
    * .../texts/finnish/1992/UT.tar.gz
    * .../texts/finnish/1992/COPYRIGHT (read also this!)

Finnish 1938 version
    * .../texts/finnish/1933,38/VT.tar.gz
    * .../texts/finnish/1933,38/UT.tar.gz

Swedish year 1917 version
    * .../texts/swedish/bibeln-3.7.tar.gz

Louis Segond 1910 version
    * .../texts/french/lsg.tar.gz

@{u}The Aminet archive is:@{uu}

    * docs/etext/LutherBibel.lha

@{u}Still waiting for release from Pascal Marcelin (announced at BibVision WWW site)@{uu}

    * the French John Nelson Darby translation

Note: you probably can download at least the KJV and Vulgate versions also from
other FTP sites maybe nearer to you. But, I cannot guarantee BibVision parsing
routines work with other sites' files; so if you think the files are not the
same, refer to the archives mentioned above.


@{u}Unarchiving the archives@{uu}

After you have loaded a Bible archive, unarchive the files to some temporary
directory. I've used UnArc (comes with OS 4 distribution) but other
unarchivers can be used. Note that most files are stored in .tar.gz form. This
file is unarchived to a single file (UT.tar.gz to UT) and you must still
unarchive this file with UnArc to the individual book files
(1mooses,2mooses,...). The Luther Bible is an exception, it's a LhA- compressed
file containing the whole Bible in a single file.

After unarchiving, you should use @{"Project/Create index" link "PROJECT" 0} menu item to parse and
save the files in a special compressed form. After this, the archives and their
contents are redundant and can be deleted.

BibVision uses Martin Merz's AISS image set for its' gadgets if available. You
can download it from @{"http://www.masonicons.info " system "OS4:C/URLOpen http://www.masonicons.info"}

@endnode

@node "STARTING" "Starting BibVision"
You can start BibVision from both the Shell and the WorkBench. With shell
arguments or WorkBench icon tool types you can modify the way program starts.


@{u}Starting from shell@{uu}

Type

@{b}BibVision <args>@{ub}

where args are optional and may be

PUBSCREEN <screenname>
 - the name of the public screen you want BibVision to open on

SETTINGS <filename>
 - obsolete but included to not break scripts

BIBLE <dirname>
 - the directory holding the indexed Bible you want to open

BOOK <bookname>
 - the name of the book (in the current locale) you want to open

CHAPTER <number>
 - the number of the chapter to start with

VERSE <number>
 - the number of the verse to start with

BOOKMARKS <filename>
 - the bookmarks file


@{u}Starting from the WorkBench@{uu}

Click either the BibVision program icon or one of the project icons saved into
the directories holding a Bible. You may modify the tool types to change
program's default starting values. The tool types are similar to the Shell
arguments, see above:

PUBSCREEN=<screenname>
 - the name of the public screen you want BibVision to open on

USETOOLPOS
 - if specified and no settings option 'Use previous position at startup'
   is selected, starts BibVision at position defined by BIBLE, BOOK,
   CHAPTER, VERSE tooltypes

BIBLE=<dirname>
 - the directory holding the indexed Bible you want to open

BOOK=<bookname>
 - the name of the book (in the current locale) you want to open

CHAPTER=<number>
 - the number of the chapter to start with

VERSE=<number>
 - the number of the verse to start with

BOOKMARKS=<filename>
 - the bookmarks file
@endnode

@node "CREATEINDEX" "Creating Bible Index"
@{u}Bible index@{uu}

The bible index is a compressed and easy-to-search-quickly version of the Bible
translation text which BibVision uses to display and search the Bible texts.
Before the Bible can be used in BibVision, you must create the index from the
Bible source text files found in the Internet FTP site, see @{"installation" link "INSTALLATION" 0}.


@{u}How to create an index@{uu}

1. Uncompress the Bible texts to a temporary directory. This may take about 5-6
MB.

2. Choose @{"Project/Create index" link "PROJECT" 0} menu item. The index creation requester
appears.

3. Set the @{b}Type@{ub} pulldown menu according to the Bible version you are about to
parse. It's important to set this right, as BibVision uses the type data to
find the file names of the individual books. It directly affects also the way
the files are interpreted.

4. Set the @{b}Source@{ub} to the directory your @{"unarchived files" link "INSTALLATION" 0} reside. The
@{b}Destination@{ub} is automatically set to the default destination directory (relative
to program's directory) according to the Type.

Normally you should use the default setting as the install script has created
the directory for you. If you want to use some other directory, choose it.
Remember you can create a new directory "on the fly" by using the ASL file
requester's "Create Directory" menu item.

5. Click the @{b}Create@{ub} gadget. Indexing starts and will take a long time depending
on the speed of your computer, may be several minutes. If you want to cancel
the ongoing indexing, click the @{b}Stop@{ub} gadget in the opened progress requester.
Note that for context switch reasons, the indexing stops only after the current
book file has been handled. It can take several seconds - you don't have to
click Stop repeatedly and wonder why nothing happens.


After the fuelgauge has been filled, the Bible index is ready and has hopefully
been saved to your destination directory. You may delete the source Bible text
files if you wish, they are not used anymore.

See @{"Opening bible" link "OPENING" 0} and @{"Using Bible Window" link "USINGWINDOW" 0} to get info how to use this indexed
Bible.
@endnode

@node "OPENING" "Opening Bibles and Books"
@{u}Opening a Bible@{uu}

Before you can read your Bible books you have to open Bible. This may be done
by

    * choosing @{"Project/Open Bible" link "PROJECT" 0} menu item or the
      "Open Bible" icon on the left end of window toolbar to select
      the directory Bible resides in

    * entering the name of the Bible (directory) to
      a @{"project icon tooltype" link "STARTING" 0} and starting BibVision
      by clicking this icon

    * selecting option 'Use previous position at startup' in Settings requester,
      BibVision will start at the position one was browsing at when the program
      exited last time

In a Bible window you can have only one Bible opened at a time. To read
simultaneously multiple Bible versions open a new window for each Bible.
 You can also have multiple windows with the same Bible. Note that every time
you open a new window the first thing to do is to open a Bible in it.

@{u}Opening a book@{uu}

As you have successfully opened a Bible you are asked for a book to be opened.
If you cancel this requester or if you later want to change the book opened,
simply click the book choosing gadget at the browser part of the window
@endnode

@node "SEARCHING" "Searching"
BibVision does have quite a powerful and relatively fast search engine. You
have two ways to search what you want:

    * searching in the current book, starting in the current position
    * searching multiple chosen books, starting in the first chosen book

For both versions the search pattern is entered the same way. The program uses
AmigaDOS pattern matching (Jo* matches for Joshua, John, Joachim etc.) The
special feature is that you use a multi-word search pattern, each word is
handled separately: ("Jo* clim*" matches "Joshua climbed", "John climbs" etc).

@{u}To do a simple (in current book) search@{uu}

    * select @{"Edit/Search" link "EDIT" 0} menu item or the Search icon on window
      toolbar to open search requester
    * set the pattern to be searched into the string gadget
    * click @{b}Search@{ub} gadget

If found, the view is moved to the place word was found. If not found, a
requester is shown about this. To find the next occasion choose @{"Edit/Search" link "EDIT" 0}
@{"Next" link "EDIT" 0} menu item or the appropriate icon in window toolbar.

@{u}To do a multi-book search@{uu}

    * select @{"Edit/Search" link "EDIT" 0} menu item to open search requester
    * set the pattern to be searched into the string gadget
    * click @{b}Search Selected@{ub} gadget

A progress requester is shown while searching; you can stop the search with the
Stop gadget after the book currently searched has been completed. Otherwise the
multi-book search works like in the simple search.

@{u}For King James Version readers a note!@{uu} Due to the algorithm, the search won't
find word "Jesus" as itself, but if you use pattern matching "Jesu*",
everything works okay. Technical explanation: KJV has "Jesus" written also
"JESUS" and this is the version the non-pattern matching routine tries to
search. No other workarounds yet, I'm tired of making them because of the
inconsistencies of the source files (quite many, actually).
@endnode

@node "USINGWINDOW" "Using the Bible window"
@{u}Using the BibVision Window@{uu}

On the upper part of the BibVision window there is a row of gadgets:
    * Open Bible
    * Search
    * Search next
    * Browse window history back
    * Browse window history forward

The lower part of the window is divided into two areas: the bookmark list and
the book browser.

The bookmarks are positions in the Bible that you have marked up to be able to
refer them later easily. The positions are grouped under one or more groups.
See the included @{"example screenshot" link "example1.jpg/main" 0} to get the idea. You are able to save
bookmarks to a file for later reference and load them through either a menu
item or a Shell argument / Workbench tooltype. The gadgets for handling the
list are
    * Add a bookmark (to selected group)
    * Add a group
    * Remove selected bookmark/group
    * Move selected bookmark/group up
    * Move selected bookmark/group down

The window's book browser area has gadgets for selecting the book you are
reading and selecting the chapter & verse. If you have several windows open,
clicking @{b}Synchronize@{ub} gadget sets all windows to the same book, chapter and
verse as in the window you are currently viewing.

The book is shown with a simple text.datatype instance and you can move around
in it either by

    * using the scroller gadgets with mouse
    * using the mouse scroll wheel
    * using the cursor keys in the keyboard
    * using chapter and verse gadgets
    * using browse back/forward window history gadgets in window toolbar
    * using bookmark entries (double click)


@{u}Copying to clipboard@{uu}

You can copy text from a viewed book simply clicking the let mouse button on
the position you want to be the start and the drag-selecting the area. When you
release the button,

    * the selected are remains higlighted and you either click 'Copy' gadget,
      select Edit/Copy menu item or type RAmiga-C (OS4.1)

After this you can paste the text for example to a document you are editing in a text editor.
@endnode

@node "MULTIPLEBIBLES" "Using multiple Bibles and Books together"
What if you want to compare different translations, or different books in the
same Bible, or different places in the same book? BibVision has some handy
features for this. You can open multiple windows with @{"Project/New window" link "PROJECT" 0} menu
item. The windows are completely independent so you can open the same or
another Bible to each window with @{"Project/Open Bible" link "PROJECT" 0} menu item.

One of the most useful features of BibVision is synchronizing. By clicking the
@{b}Synchronize@{ub} gadget at the browser area of the window all other windows move to
the same book and chapter & verse as the current window.
@endnode

@node "PROJECT" "Project Menu"
@{u}Project menu@{uu}


Project/New Window
    Opens a new window for displaying another Bible. Within this window
    you can open another Bible translation and book, or you can open
    the same Bible and even the same book to see and compare. The windows
    are fully independent.

Project/Open
    Opens a new Bible to this window. This menu item causes an ASL
    requester to oen and you choose the directory containing the
    @{"pre-indexed" link "CREATEINDEX" 0} Bible. After this, you have to choose the book to
    be read in the window, too.

Project/Create index
    See separate section on @{"creating indices" link "CREATEINDEX" 0}.

Project/Information
    Tells the facts of the current BibVision version running.

Project/Help
    Opens this manual (must be in the program directory)

Project/Iconify
    Iconifies the current window to Workbench. The icon used is the
    default project icon of the system.

Project/Quit
    Closes this window and - if last - quits the program.
@endnode

@node "EDIT" "Edit Menu"
@{u}Edit menu@{uu}

Edit/Copy
    Copies selected text into clipboard (at OS4.1)

Edit/Search
    Opens a @{"search requester" link "SEARCHING" 0} where you can enter the word(s) to
    be searched and also define the book(s) in which the search is made.
    Note that if you type a multi-word search pattern, each word
    is handled separately so you can use AmigaDOS wildcards in
    each word ("Jo* clim*" matches "Joshua climbed", "John climbs" etc).

Edit/Search next
    Searches the next match for a pattern. The pattern must be
    set first by Edit/Search menu item.
@endnode

@node "SETTINGS" "Settings Menu"
@{u}Settings Menu@{uu}

Settings/Edit
    Opens the Settings requester. Current options

        * Line length: this is the line length for book display (affects only
          after you open the book to be read for the next time)

        * Temporary text directory: the human-readable form of Bible books
          are generated from the indexed Bible files to this directory.

        * Keep texts at exit: the above-mentioned text files are deleted
          every time BibVision quits, unless this option is selected. By
          selecting this the book opening is quicker but it takes some
          disk space.

        * Show hints: if selected, the 'bubble help' info texts are
          shown when mouse pointer stops over gadget.

        * Center window: if selected, a new window is initially centered
          on screen. If not selected, the last window position saved at
          program exit is used for new windows.

        * Use previous position at startup: if selected, BibVision will
          start at the same browsing position where it was when BibVision
          quitted last time.

        * Create icons: if selected, BibVision creates project icons into
          Bible directories when creating index. The icons can be for
          example dropped into Workbench or AmiDock dock for quick start

Settings/Load Bookmarks
    Loads previously saved bookmarks from file with user-defined file name.

Settings/Save Bookmarks
    Saves current bookmarks to file with user-defined file name.

Note: as of version 2.0, BibVision no longer supports opening and saving
named settings files. The settings are loaded and saved automatically at
startup/program exit by application.library PrefsObjects system.
@endnode

